# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-internationalization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] The **`Intl.DateTimeFormat`** object enables language-sensitive date and time formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] Creates a new `Intl.DateTimeFormat` object.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] Returns an array containing those of the provided locales that are supported without having to fall back to the runtime's default locale.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] These properties are defined on `Intl.DateTimeFormat.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.DateTimeFormat` instances.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] For `Intl.DateTimeFormat` instances, the initial value is the `Intl.DateTimeFormat` constructor.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl.DateTimeFormat"`.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] Getter function that formats a date according to the locale and formatting options of this `DateTimeFormat` object.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] This method receives two Dates and formats the date range in the most concise way based on the locale and options provided when instantiating `DateTimeFormat`.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] This method receives two Dates and returns an Array of objects containing the locale-specific tokens representing each part of the formatted date range.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] Returns an `Array` of objects representing the date string in parts that can be used for custom locale-aware formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] Returns a new object with properties reflecting the locale and formatting options computed during initialization of the object.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] In basic use without specifying a locale, `DateTimeFormat` uses the default locale and default options.
[src:web-internationalization/datetimeformat] This example shows some of the variations in localized date and time formats.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] The **`lang`** global attribute helps define the language of an element: the language that non-editable elements are written in, or the language that the editable elements should be written in by the user.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] The attribute contains a single BCP 47 language tag.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] If the attribute value is the *empty string* (`lang=""`), the language is set to *unknown*; if the language tag is not valid according to BCP47, it is set to *invalid*.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] Even if the `lang` attribute is set, it may not be taken into account, as the `xml:lang` attribute has priority.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] For the CSS pseudo-class `:lang`, two invalid language names are different if their names are different.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] WCAG Success Criterion 3.1.1 **requires** that a page language is specified in a way which may be 'programmatically determined' (i.e., via the **`lang`** attribute).
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] WCAG Success Criterion 3.1.2 requires that pages with **parts** in different languages have the languages of those parts specified too.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] Again, the **`lang`** attribute is the correct mechanism for this.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] The purpose of these requirements is primarily to allow assistive technologies such as screen readers to invoke the correct pronunciation.
[src:web-internationalization/global-attributes-lang] If an element has no `lang` attribute, it will inherit the `lang` value set on its parent node, which in turn may inherit it from its parent, and so on.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The **`Intl`** namespace object contains several constructors as well as functionality common to the internationalization constructors and other language sensitive functions.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Collectively, they comprise the ECMAScript Internationalization API, which provides language sensitive string comparison, number formatting, date and time formatting, and more.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Unlike most global objects, `Intl` is not a constructor.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `Intl` object as a function.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] All properties and methods of `Intl` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The `locales` argument is used to determine the locale used in a given operation.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The JavaScript implementation examines `locales`, and then computes a locale it understands that comes closest to satisfying the expressed preference.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] In the latter two cases, the actual locale used is the best-supported locale determined by locale negotiation.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] If a locale identifier is not a string or an object, a `TypeError` is thrown.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] If a locale identifier is a string that's syntactically invalid, a `RangeError` is thrown.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] If a locale identifier is well-formed but the implementation doesn't recognize it, it is ignored and the next locale in the list is considered, eventually falling back to the system's locale.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] However, you shouldn't rely on a particular locale name being ignored, because the implementation may add data for any locale in the future.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] For example, `new Intl.DateTimeFormat("default")` uses the implementation's default locale only because `"default"` is syntactically valid but not recognized as any locale.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Each subtag and sequence are separated by hyphens.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Locale identifiers are case-insensitive ASCII.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] However, it's conventional to use title case (the first letter is capitalized, successive letters are lower case) for script subtags, upper case for region subtags, and lower case for everything else.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Subtags identifying languages, scripts, regions (including countries), and (rarely used) variants are registered in the IANA Language Subtag Registry.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] This registry is periodically updated over time, and implementations may not always be up to date, so don't rely too much on subtags being universally supported.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] BCP 47 extension sequences consist of a single digit or letter (other than `"x"`) and one or more two- to eight-letter or digit subtags separated by hyphens.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Only one sequence is permitted for each digit or letter: `"de-a-foo-a-foo"` is invalid.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] BCP 47 extension subtags are defined in the Unicode CLDR Project.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Finally, a private-use extension sequence using the letter `"x"` may appear, followed by one or more one- to eight-letter or digit subtags separated by hyphens.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] This allows applications to encode information for their own private use, that will be ignored by all `Intl` operations.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The `options` argument must be an object with properties that vary between constructors and functions.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] If the `options` argument is not provided or is undefined, default values are used for all properties.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] One property is supported by all language sensitive constructors and functions: The `localeMatcher` property, whose value must be a string `"lookup"` or `"best fit"` and which selects one of the locale matching algorithms described below.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The list of locales specified by the `locales` argument, after Unicode extensions have been removed from them, is interpreted as a prioritized request from the application.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The runtime compares it against the locales it has available and picks the best one available.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Two matching algorithms exist: the `"lookup"` matcher follows the Lookup algorithm specified in BCP 47; the `"best fit"` matcher lets the runtime provide a locale that's at least, but possibly more, suited for the request than the result of the Lookup algorithm.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] If the application doesn't provide a `locales` argument, or the runtime doesn't have a locale that matches the request, then the runtime's default locale is used.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The matcher can be selected using a property of the `options` argument (see below).
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] If the selected locale identifier had a Unicode extension sequence, that extension is now used to customize the constructed object or the behavior of the function.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Each constructor or function supports only a subset of the keys defined for the Unicode extension, and the supported values often depend on the locale identifier.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] For example, the `"co"` key (collation) is only supported by `Intl.Collator`, and its `"phonebk"` value is only supported for German.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for collators, which are objects that enable language-sensitive string comparison.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable language-sensitive date and time formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable the consistent translation of language, region and script display names.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable locale-sensitive duration formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable language-sensitive list formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that represents a Unicode locale identifier.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable language-sensitive number formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable plural-sensitive formatting and language-specific rules for plurals.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable language-sensitive relative time formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Constructor for objects that enable locale-sensitive text segmentation.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl"`.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Returns a sorted array containing the supported unique calendar, collation, currency, numbering systems, or unit values supported by the implementation.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] Alternatively, the `navigator.languages` property provides a sorted list of the user's preferred languages.
[src:web-internationalization/global-objects-intl] This list can be passed directly to the `Intl` constructors to implement preference-based fallback selection of locales.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] An **IETF BCP 47 language tag** is a standardized code that is used to identify human languages on the Internet.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The tag structure has been standardized by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in *Best Current Practice (BCP) 47*; the subtags are maintained by the *IANA Language Subtag Registry*.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] To distinguish language variants for countries, regions, or writing systems (scripts), IETF language tags combine subtags from other standards such as ISO 639, ISO 15924, ISO 3166-1 and UN M.49.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] It is used by computing standards such as HTTP, HTML, XML and PNG.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] IETF language tags were first defined in Request for comment 1766, edited by Harald Tveit Alvestrand, published in March 1995.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The tags used ISO 639 two-letter language codes and ISO 3166 two-letter country codes, and allowed registration of whole tags that included variant or script subtags of three to eight letters.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] In January 2001, this was updated by RFC 3066, which added the use of ISO 639-2 three-letter codes, permitted subtags with digits, and adopted the concept of language ranges from HTTP/1.1 to help with matching of language tags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The next revision of the specification came in September 2006 with the publication of RFC 4646—the main part of the specification—edited by Addison Philips and Mark Davis, and RFC 4647—which deals with matching behaviour.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] RFC 4646 introduced a more structured format for language tags, added the use of ISO 15924 four-letter script codes and UN M.49 three-digit geographical region codes, and replaced the old registry of tags with a new registry of subtags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The small number of previously defined tags that did not conform to the new structure were grandfathered in order to maintain compatibility with RFC 3066.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The current version of the specification, RFC 5646, was published in September 2009.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The main purpose of this revision was to incorporate three-letter codes from ISO 639-3 and 639-5 into the Language Subtag Registry, in order to increase the interoperability between ISO 639 and BCP 47.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Each language tag is composed of one or more "subtags" separated by hyphens (-).
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Each subtag is composed only of either basic Latin letters or digits.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Subtags are not case-sensitive, but the specification recommends using the same case as in the Language Subtag Registry, where region subtags are UPPERCASE, script subtags are title case, and all other subtags are lowercase.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] This capitalization follows the recommendations of the underlying ISO standards.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Optional script and region subtags are preferred to be omitted when they add no distinguishing information to a language tag.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] For example, *es* is preferred over *es-Latn*, as Spanish is fully expected to be written in the Latin script; *ja* is preferred over *ja-JP*, as Japanese *as used in Japan* does not differ markedly from Japanese as used elsewhere.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Not all linguistic regions can be represented with a valid region subtag: the subnational regional dialects of a primary language are registered as variant subtags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] For example, the *valencia* variant subtag for the Valencian variant of the Catalan is registered in the Language Subtag Registry with the prefix *ca*.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] As this dialect is spoken almost exclusively in Spain, the region subtag *ES* can normally be omitted.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Furthermore, there are script tags that do not refer to traditional scripts such as Latin, or even scripts at all, and these usually begin with a *Z.* For example, *Zsye* refers to emojis, *Zmth* to mathematical notation, *Zxxx* to unwritten documents and *Zyyy* to undetermined scripts.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] IETF language tags have been used as locale identifiers in many applications.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] It may be necessary for these applications to establish their own strategy for defining, encoding and matching locales if the strategy described in RFC 4647 is not adequate.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The use, interpretation and matching of IETF language tags is currently defined in RFC 5646 and RFC 4647.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The Language Subtag Registry lists all currently valid public subtags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Private-use subtags are not included in the Registry as they are implementation-dependent and subject to private agreements between third parties using them.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] These private agreements are out of scope of BCP 47.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The following is a list of some of the more commonly used primary language subtags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The list represents only a small subset (less than 2 percent) of primary language subtags; for full information, the Language Subtag Registry should be consulted directly.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Although some types of subtags are derived from ISO or UN core standards, they do not follow these standards absolutely, as this could lead to the meaning of language tags changing over time.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] In particular, a subtag derived from a code assigned by ISO 639, ISO 15924, ISO 3166, or UN M49 remains a valid (though deprecated) subtag even if the code is withdrawn from the corresponding core standard.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] If the standard later assigns a new meaning to the withdrawn code, the corresponding subtag will still retain its old meaning.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] This stability was introduced in RFC 4646.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] RFC 4646 defined the concept of an "extended language subtag" (sometimes referred to as *extlang*), although no such subtags were registered at that time.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] RFC 5645 and RFC 5646 added primary language subtags corresponding to ISO 639-3 codes for all languages that did not already exist in the Registry.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] In addition, codes for languages encompassed by certain macrolanguages were registered as extended language subtags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Sign languages were also registered as extlangs, with the prefix *sgn*.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] These languages may be represented either with the subtag for the encompassed language alone (*cmn* for Mandarin) or with a language-extlang combination (*zh-cmn*).
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The first option is preferred for most purposes.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The second option is called "extlang form" and is new in RFC 5646.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Whole tags that were registered prior to RFC 4646 and are now classified as "grandfathered" or "redundant" (depending on whether they fit the new syntax) are deprecated in favor of the corresponding ISO 639-3–based language subtag, if one exists.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] To list a few examples, *nan* is preferred over *zh-min-nan* for Min Nan Chinese; *hak* is preferred over *i-hak* and *zh-hakka* for Hakka Chinese; and *ase* is preferred over *sgn-US* for American Sign Language.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Windows Vista and later versions of Microsoft Windows have RFC 4646 support.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] ISO 639-5 defines language collections with alpha-3 codes in a different way than they were initially encoded in ISO 639-2 (including one code already present in ISO 639-1, Bihari coded inclusively as *bh* in ISO 639-1 and *bih* in ISO 639-2).
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Specifically, the language collections are now all defined in ISO 639-5 as inclusive, rather than some of them being defined exclusively.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] This means that language collections have a broader scope than before, in some cases where they could encompass languages that were already encoded separately within ISO 639-2.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] For example, the ISO 639-2 code *afa* was previously associated with the name "Afro-Asiatic (Other)", excluding languages such as Arabic that already had their own code.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] In ISO 639-5, this collection is named "Afro-Asiatic languages" and includes all such languages.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] ISO 639-2 changed the exclusive names in 2009 to match the inclusive ISO 639-5 names.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] BCP 47 defines a "Scope" property to identify subtags for language collections.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] However, it does not define any given collection as inclusive or exclusive, and does not use the ISO 639-5 grouping type attribute, although the description fields in the Language Subtag Registry for these subtags match the ISO 639-5 (inclusive) names.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] As a consequence, BCP 47 language tags that include a primary language subtag for a collection may be ambiguous as to whether the collection is intended to be inclusive or exclusive.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] ISO 639-5 does not define precisely which languages are members of these collections; only the hierarchical classification of collections is defined, using the inclusive definition of these collections.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Because of this, RFC 5646 does not recommend the use of subtags for language collections for most applications, although they are still preferred over subtags whose meaning is even less specific, such as "Multiple languages" and "Undetermined".
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] In contrast, the classification of individual languages within their macrolanguage is standardized, in both ISO 639-3 and the Language Subtag Registry.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Script subtags were first added to the Language Subtag Registry when RFC 4646 was published, from the list of codes defined in ISO 15924.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] They are encoded in the language tag after primary and extended language subtags, but before other types of subtag, including region and variant subtags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Some primary language subtags are defined with a property named "Suppress-Script" which indicates the cases where a single script can usually be assumed by default for the language, even if it can be written with another script.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] When this is the case, it is preferable to omit the script subtag, to improve the likelihood of successful matching.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] A different script subtag can still be appended to make the distinction when necessary.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] For example, *yi* is preferred over *yi-Hebr* in most contexts, because the Hebrew script subtag is assumed for the Yiddish language.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] As another example, *zh-Hans-SG* may be considered equivalent to *zh-Hans*, because the region code is probably not significant; the written form of Chinese used in Singapore uses the same simplified Chinese characters as in other countries where Chinese is written.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] However, the script subtag is maintained because it is significant.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] ISO 15924 includes some codes for script variants (for example, *Hans* and *Hant* for simplified and traditional forms of Chinese characters) that are unified within Unicode and ISO/IEC 10646.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] They may occasionally be useful in language tags to expose orthographic or semantic differences, with different analysis of letters, diacritics, and digraphs/trigraphs as default grapheme clusters, or differences in letter casing rules.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Two-letter region subtags are based on codes assigned, or "exceptionally reserved", in ISO 3166-1.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] If the ISO 3166 Maintenance Agency were to reassign a code that had previously been assigned to a different country, the existing BCP 47 subtag corresponding to that code would retain its meaning, and a new region subtag based on UN M.49 would be registered for the new country.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] UN M.49 is also the source for numeric region subtags for geographical regions, such as `005` for South America.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The UN M.49 codes for economic regions are not allowed.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Region subtags are used to specify the variety of a language "as used in" a particular region.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] They are appropriate when the variety is regional in nature, and can be captured adequately by identifying the countries involved, as when distinguishing British English (*en-GB*) from American English (*en-US*).
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] When the difference is one of script or script variety, as for simplified versus traditional Chinese characters, it should be expressed with a script subtag instead of a region subtag; in this example, *zh-Hans* and *zh-Hant* should be used instead of *zh-CN/zh-SG/zh-MY* and *zh-TW/zh-HK/zh-MO*.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] When a distinct language subtag exists for a language that could be considered a regional variety, it is often preferable to use the more specific subtag instead of a language-region combination.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] For example, *ar-DZ* (Arabic as used in Algeria) may be better expressed as *arq* for Algerian Spoken Arabic.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Disagreements about language identification may extend to BCP 47 and to the core standards that inform it.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] BCP 47 delegates this type of judgment to the core standards, and does not attempt to overrule or supersede them.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Variant subtags and (theoretically) primary language subtags may be registered individually, but not in a way that contradicts the core standards.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Extension subtags are composed of multiple hyphen-separated character strings, starting with a single character (other than *x*), called a *singleton*.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Each extension is described in its own IETF RFC, which identifies a Registration Authority to manage the data for that extension.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] IANA is responsible for allocating singletons.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Two extensions have been assigned as of January 2014.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Extension T allows a language tag to include information on how the tagged data was transliterated, transcribed, or otherwise transformed.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] For example, the tag *en-t-jp* could be used for content in English that was translated from the original Japanese.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Additional substrings could indicate that the translation was done mechanically, or in accordance with a published standard.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Extension T is described in the informational RFC 6497, published in February 2012.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] The Registration Authority is the Unicode Consortium.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Extension U allows a wide variety of locale attributes found in the Common Locale Data Repository (CLDR) to be embedded in language tags.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Extension U is described in the informational RFC 6067, published in December 2010.
[src:web-internationalization/ietf-language-tag] Its LDML specification, published as UTS 35, serves as the documentation of registered attributes and keywords.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] In computing, **internationalization and localization** (American) or **internationalisation and localisation** (Commonwealth), often abbreviated **i18n** and **l10n** respectively, are means of adapting to different languages, regional peculiarities and technical requirements of a target locale.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Internationalization is the process of designing a software application so that it can be adapted to various languages and regions without engineering changes.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Localization is the process of adapting internationalized software for a specific region or language by translating text and adding locale-specific components.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Localization (which is potentially performed multiple times, for different locales) uses the infrastructure or flexibility provided by internationalization (which is ideally performed only once before localization, or as an integral part of ongoing development).
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Some writers have the latter term capitalized (*L10n*) to help distinguish the two.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Some companies, like IBM and Oracle, use the term *globalization*, *g11n*, for the combination of internationalization and localization.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Microsoft defines internationalization as a combination of world-readiness and localization.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] World-readiness is a developer task, which enables a product to be used with multiple scripts and cultures (globalization) and separates user interface resources in a localizable format (localizability, abbreviated to *L12y*).
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Hewlett-Packard and HP-UX created a system called "National Language Support" or "Native Language Support" (NLS) to produce localizable software.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Some vendors, including IBM use the term *National Language Version* (NLV) for localized versions of software products supporting only one specific locale.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The term implies the existence of other alike NLV versions of the software for different markets; this terminology is not used where no internationalization and localization was undertaken and a software product only supports one language and locale in any version.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Translation is typically the most time-consuming component of language localization.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Computer software can encounter differences above and beyond straightforward translation of words and phrases, because computer programs can generate content dynamically.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] These differences may need to be taken into account by the internationalization process in preparation for translation.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Many of these differences are so regular that a conversion between languages can be easily automated.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The Common Locale Data Repository by Unicode provides a collection of such differences.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Its data is used by major operating systems, including Microsoft Windows, macOS and Debian, and by major Internet companies or projects such as Google and the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] In particular, the United States and Europe differ in most of these cases.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Specific third-party services, such as online maps, weather reports, or payment service providers, might not be available worldwide from the same carriers, or at all.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Time zones vary across the world, and this must be taken into account if a product originally only interacted with people in a single time zone.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] For internationalization, UTC is often used internally and then converted into a local time zone for display purposes.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] To *internationalize* a product, it is important to look at a variety of markets that the product will foreseeably enter.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] A broader approach takes into account cultural factors regarding for example the adaptation of the business process logic or the inclusion of individual cultural (behavioral) aspects.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Already in the 1990s, companies such as Bull used machine translation (Systran) on a large scale, for all their translation activity: human translators handled pre-editing (making the input machine-readable) and post-editing.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Both in re-engineering an existing software or designing a new internationalized software, the first step of internationalization is to split each potentially locale-dependent part (whether code, text or data) into a separate module.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Each module can then either rely on a standard library/dependency or be independently replaced as needed for each locale.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The current prevailing practice is for applications to place text in resource files which are loaded during program execution as needed.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] These strings, stored in resource files, are relatively easy to translate.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Programs are often built to reference resource libraries depending on the selected locale data.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The storage for translatable and translated strings is sometimes called a message catalog as the strings are called messages.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The catalog generally comprises a set of files in a specific localization format and a standard library to handle said format.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] One software library and format that aids this is gettext.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Thus to get an application to support multiple languages one would design the application to select the relevant language resource file at runtime.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The code required to manage data entry verification and many other locale-sensitive data types also must support differing locale requirements.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Modern development systems and operating systems include sophisticated libraries for international support of these types, see also Standard locale data above.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Many localization issues (e.g. writing direction, text sorting) require more profound changes in the software than text translation.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] For example, OpenOffice.org achieves this with compilation switches.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] A globalization method includes, after planning, three implementation steps: internationalization, localization and quality assurance.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] To some degree (e.g. for quality assurance), development teams include someone who handles the basic/central stages of the process which then enables all the others.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Such persons typically understand foreign languages and cultures and have some technical background.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Specialized technical writers are required to construct a culturally appropriate syntax for potentially complicated concepts, coupled with engineering resources to deploy and test the localization elements.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Once properly internationalized, software can rely on more decentralized models for localization: free and open source software usually rely on self-localization by end-users and volunteers, sometimes organized in teams.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The GNOME project, for example, has volunteer translation teams for over 100 languages.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] MediaWiki supports over 500 languages, of which 100 are mostly complete as of September 2023.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] When translating existing text to other languages, it is difficult to maintain the parallel versions of texts throughout the life of the product.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] For instance, if a message displayed to the user is modified, all of the translated versions must be changed.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Independent software vendors such as Microsoft may provides reference software localization guidelines for developers.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The software localization language may be different from the written language.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] In a commercial setting, the benefit of localization is access to more markets.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] In the early 1980s, Lotus 1-2-3 took two years to separate program code and text and lost the market lead in Europe over Microsoft Multiplan.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] By 1985 about a quarter of Ashton-Tate's $80 million in annual sales came from outside the United States; the company localized its products in 11 European languages.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] MicroPro found that using an Austrian translator for the West German market caused its WordStar documentation to, an executive said, not "have the tone it should have had".
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] When Tandy Corporation needed French and German translations of English error messages for the TRS-80 Model 4, the company's Belgium office and five translators in the US produced six different versions that varied depending on the gender of computer components.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] However, there are considerable costs involved, which go far beyond engineering.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Further, business operations must adapt to manage the production, storage and distribution of multiple discrete localized products, which are often being sold in completely different currencies, regulatory environments and tax regimes.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Finally, sales, marketing and technical support must also facilitate their operations in the new languages, to support customers for the localized products.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Particularly for relatively small language populations, it may never be economically viable to offer a localized product.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] One example of the pitfalls of localization is the attempt made by Microsoft to keep some keyboard shortcuts significant in local languages.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] This has resulted in some (but not all) programs in the Italian version of Microsoft Office using "CTRL + S" (*sottolineato*) as a replacement for "CTRL + U" (underline), rather than the (almost) universal "Save" function.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Before the advent of 'AutoSave', the net result could be a lot of underlined words in an unsaved revision of the document.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] The team responsible for Microsoft Excel localization decided to translate the tokens used in formulas, as a byproduct of localizing number and date formats.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] For example, =SUM(A1:A10) becomes =SOMME(A1:A10) in French or =SUMME(A1:A10) in German.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] While making the formulas easier to understand for users with no knowledge of the English language, it has also meant that, before machine translation of web pages, a search for help on the internet could not count on examples from other languages.
[src:web-internationalization/internationalization-and-localization] Manuals and tutorials required translations of every formula in examples and exercises.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] The **`Intl.NumberFormat`** object enables language-sensitive number formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] These properties are defined on `Intl.NumberFormat.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.NumberFormat` instances.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] For `Intl.NumberFormat` instances, the initial value is the `Intl.NumberFormat` constructor.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl.NumberFormat"`.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] Getter function that formats a number according to the locale and formatting options of this `Intl.NumberFormat` object.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] Getter function that formats a range of numbers according to the locale and formatting options of the `Intl.NumberFormat` object from which the method is called.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] Returns an `Array` of objects representing the range of number strings in parts that can be used for custom locale-aware formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] Returns an `Array` of objects representing the number string in parts that can be used for custom locale-aware formatting.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] Returns a new object with properties reflecting the locale and collation options computed during initialization of the object.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] In basic use without specifying a locale, a formatted string in the default locale and with default options is returned.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] This example shows some of the variations in localized number formats.
[src:web-internationalization/numberformat] For an exhaustive list of options, see the `Intl.NumberFormat()` constructor page.
